{ Seeing the slight disaster that happened in the intro, what is the best move here? }
1... g6! { Is correct! One of the main types of blunder beginners make is related to some sort of tactic. Either a threat, or a GM supported 20 move combination that leads to a lost Queen and Pawn endgame. Either way, basically the same.
If you had made one of the alternative moves, let me introduce the first rule of the study:
ALWAYS think ahead.
In short, NEVER make one-move threats because they make you 'feel good.' NEVER play a move defending something and just call it a day. } (1... Nf6 { Unfortunately, you must have either skipped the Introduction where I explained the premise of this study, or have tried alcohol for the first time. Try again. Not the alcohol, the move. } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Gh5f7] }) (1... Qe7 { At least you had the state of mind to see that f7 was under attack. However, this hems in your f8 Bishop whom is obviously not very happy with your move. Play the correct move, ...g6, instead. }) (1... Qf6 { Is an alternative. At least you had the state of mind to see that f7 was under attack. However, your horse on g8 must be extremely offended that his optimal developing square has been obstructed. Play the correct move, ...g6, instead. }) (1... Nh6 { Is an alternative. At least you had the state of mind to see that f7 was under attack. However, your horse on g8 must be extremely offended that you stuffed him to the edge of the board. Play the correct move, ...g6, instead. }) (1... d5 { Is incorrect. At least you had the state of mind to see that f7 was under attack. However, your soldier is not very happy that he has been sent on a kamikaze mission. Which, doesn't achieve anything as Bxd5 renews the threat on f7. Play the correct move, ...g6, instead. }) 2. Qf3 { Another beginner type move - making useless, one-move threats. Specifically in this scenario, a threat that we have already spent a move to avoid. Develop a piece and prevent the threat to continue. } 2... Nf6 { I will not go into this line any further, as we have pretty much covered the whole thing. Let's continue. } (2... Qf6 { This is totally acceptable, and actually the second best move! The problem is, if the ladies are not traded, you are left with an awkward one on f6 blocking in your steed on g8. Play Nf6 to continue. }) (2... Qe7 { This is alright, at least defending f7. However, you must always think ahead. In this case, this move makes your majestic lady hit a brick wall on e5. Try again. }) (2... d5? { Alright. Blocking the Bishop's eyeline to f7. I like your outside-the-box idea of blocking the Bishop instead of the Queen, but you must always think ahead. In this case, what happens after Bxd5, when the threat is renewed and you have hung a pawn for no reason? }) (2... Nh6?! { This is alright, at least defending f7. However, you must always think ahead. In this case, where will your steed go after being sat on the edge? It has no future there. }) (2... Ke7? { If you thought this can prevent checkmate, think again. You are still hanging the f7 pawn and driving your king to the center. Try again. }) (2... f6?! { This defends against Qxf7#. However, weakening your pawn structure is not recommended when there are better alternative ways to go about it. Try again. }) (2... f5? { This defends against Qxf7#. However, weakening your pawn structure (and hanging a pawn) is not recommended when there are better alternative ways to go about it. Try again. }) *


