1... Be7 { In some high-level tournaments like this one in China, the time control is in the 'stage' format. In this tournament, after move 40, both sides get extra time. Song Yuxin is in this endgame, up a pawn, and a sure win. Although he only has 1 minute left, he only has to make 2 more moves before the time control, and it would be smooth sailing then. What tactic does Me. Song play to 'decide' the game? } 2. Rxe7?? { A big mistake! Or, colloquially, a blunder...
This seemed to be a clear winner: if Rxe7 Bxb4 wins a pawn AND simplifies the position. A rule of thumb, SIMPLIFIED POSITIONS ARE EASIER TO WIN.
However, Lu Shanglei steps in again, and taught me how, when low on time, to NOT TAKE RISKS. It can pay off very much. I also recall funny stories of people hitting an emote in a winning position, only to blunder and draw or, even worse, lose. Personally (forgive me for personal advertising), I never show off or hit emotes when I'm up material or anything, and I (and all of you guys too!) should only do that once the scoresheets have been signed, or the opponent places an order for a new computer once theirs, in a fit of rage, has been embedded inside their wall.
I have been taught using the saying: "The most dangerous moment in a chess game is when you are about to win." And so, I keep that with me at all times. You guys should, too. It really helps you to win. } (2. Rb7! { Great job if you found this move. Although not a tactic, it wins the game with absolutely no problems. If you played this in less than 1 minute, great job! You are better than a 2400. Unfortunately, I can't change your FIDE rating :P
Play Song's move, Rxe7, to continue. }) 2... Rxe7 { Of course, Song was here to win. Thus he plays the next move in his combination: } 3. Bxb4 { But, while he was relishing in the sweet joys of victory, Zhao Shengxin hits him with the BOMBSHELL: } 3... Rd7!! { I'm just kidding. In the actual game, once again the lower-rated scrub bows down to the higher-rated superior. He played Rea7?? and went on to lose just a few moves later.
If he had played this instead, it would've been DRAWN. Why? White must regain his Rook , or else he'd suffer a loss. Not wanted! So, Bxa3 fails to Rxd3+, with mass destruction. But after Rxd7 Zhao plays Rxd3+, forking the King and Bishop and, after K-moves Rxb4, enters a dead drawn 3v2 endgame.
The lessons lie here: don't take risks unless you can calculate them. You cannot calculate if you are low on time, thus you must not take risks if you are low on time. Save them for another time: preferably a bigger one. (haha) } *


